Wagner Labor Archives                                        HOME      MISSION STATEMENT      FELLOWSHIPS      COLD WAR FELLOWS      ABOUT THE CENTER      CURRENT EVENTS      EVENTS ARCHIVE      COLD WAR COLLECTIONS      PAPERS OF ALGER HISS      COLD WAR IN NEWS      CALL FOR PAPERS             CONTACT INFORMATION     Elmer Holmes Bobst Library, 10th Floor     70 Washington Square South     Elmer Holmes Bobst Library     (West 4th btwn LaGuardia and Greene Streets)     New York, NY 10012     Phone: 212.998.2630           COLD WAR CENTER RESEARCH COLLECTIONS:    The Cold War was a geopolitical struggle between the United States and the Soviet Union as well as an ideological conflict between revolutionary Bolshevism and liberal, capitalist democracy. This new diplomacy, which historian Arno Mayer traces to the First World War and the struggle between Woodrow Wilson and V.I. Lenin, recognized that ideas were powerful weapons. The United States and the Soviet Union presented two radically different visions of the post- World War II world as they contested the meaning of democracy, civil rights, civil liberties, labor rights, economics, culture, and society. This complex relationship between foreign and domestic policy is documented by the research collections of the Center for the United States and the Cold War.   The strengths of the Tamiment Library’s research collections as they relate to the Cold War lie in their documentation of the connections between domestic and foreign policy, law and society, and international relations and politics. Records of the Communist Party, USA and the archives of various labor unions including the Communication Workers of America, the Transport Workers Union of America, Actors Equity, United Automobile Workers District Council 65, Actors Equity, and the American Federation of Television and Radio Artists document the Cold War at home. For example, they trace ways in which some labor unions accommodated the anti-Communist crusade and even worked with American intelligence to undercut the Left and bolster the more conservative elements within the labor movement. Philip Agee’s papers describe this process in considerable detail from the point of view of a disillusioned CIA agent. Controlling revolutionary nationalism became a major Cold War battleground. This struggle began in Greece, Italy, and France in the late 1940s and continued in Iran and Guatemala in the 1950s, and reached peak intensity during the Vietnam War. Tamiment’s collections show how this worldwide conflict became a major theatre of the Cold War with important implications for the civil rights movement, the struggle to defend civil liberties, and the ways in which the United States became, to use Lizabeth Cohen’s term, a “Consumer Republic.”   Another major theme of Tamiment’s collections is the relationship among three developments: the Cold War, the business community’s efforts to roll back the New Deal, and domestic repression. Many collections, including the records of the National Lawyers Guild; the archive of the Rabinowitz and Boudin law firm; and the legal files of the Communist Party, USA document the Red Scare; the black list, particularly in the entertainment industry and the public schools; and the ways in which radicals were purged from the CIO unions. Wagner Labor Archives                                        HOME      MISSION STATEMENT      FELLOWSHIPS      COLD WAR FELLOWS      ABOUT THE CENTER      CURRENT EVENTS      EVENTS ARCHIVE      COLD WAR COLLECTIONS      PAPERS OF ALGER HISS      COLD WAR IN NEWS      CALL FOR PAPERS             CONTACT INFORMATION     Elmer Holmes Bobst Library, 10th Floor     70 Washington Square South     Elmer Holmes Bobst Library     (West 4th btwn LaGuardia and Greene Streets)     New York, NY 10012     Phone: 212.998.2630           COLD WAR CENTER RESEARCH COLLECTIONS:    The Cold War was a geopolitical struggle between the United States and the Soviet Union as well as an ideological conflict between revolutionary Bolshevism and liberal, capitalist democracy. This new diplomacy, which historian Arno Mayer traces to the First World War and the struggle between Woodrow Wilson and V.I. Lenin, recognized that ideas were powerful weapons. The United States and the Soviet Union presented two radically different visions of the post- World War II world as they contested the meaning of democracy, civil rights, civil liberties, labor rights, economics, culture, and society. This complex relationship between foreign and domestic policy is documented by the research collections of the Center for the United States and the Cold War.   The strengths of the Tamiment Library’s research collections as they relate to the Cold War lie in their documentation of the connections between domestic and foreign policy, law and society, and international relations and politics. Records of the Communist Party, USA and the archives of various labor unions including the Communication Workers of America, the Transport Workers Union of America, Actors Equity, United Automobile Workers District Council 65, Actors Equity, and the American Federation of Television and Radio Artists document the Cold War at home. For example, they trace ways in which some labor unions accommodated the anti-Communist crusade and even worked with American intelligence to undercut the Left and bolster the more conservative elements within the labor movement. Philip Agee’s papers describe this process in considerable detail from the point of view of a disillusioned CIA agent. Controlling revolutionary nationalism became a major Cold War battleground. This struggle began in Greece, Italy, and France in the late 1940s and continued in Iran and Guatemala in the 1950s, and reached peak intensity during the Vietnam War. Tamiment’s collections show how this worldwide conflict became a major theatre of the Cold War with important implications for the civil rights movement, the struggle to defend civil liberties, and the ways in which the United States became, to use Lizabeth Cohen’s term, a “Consumer Republic.”   Another major theme of Tamiment’s collections is the relationship among three developments: the Cold War, the business community’s efforts to roll back the New Deal, and domestic repression. Many collections, including the records of the National Lawyers Guild; the archive of the Rabinowitz and Boudin law firm; and the legal files of the Communist Party, USA document the Red Scare; the black list, particularly in the entertainment industry and the public schools; and the ways in which radicals were purged from the CIO unions.
